T*
(Andrej Karpathy has a gift for coining terms that quickly go mainstream. When I heard "vibe) Tj
T*
(coding," it just made sense. It perfectly captured the experience of programming without really) Tj
T*
(engaging with the code. You just vibe until the application does what you want. Then there's) Tj
T*
("hallucination." He didn't exactly invent it. The term has existed since the 1970s. In one) Tj
T*
(early instance, it was used to describe a text summarization program's failure to accurately) Tj
T*
(summarize its source material. But Karpathy's revival of the term brought it back into the) Tj
T*
(mainstream, and subtly shifted its meaning, from "prediction error" to something closer to a) Tj
T*
(dream or a vision. Now, large language models don't throw errors. They hallucinate. When they) Tj
T*
(invent facts or bend the truth, they're not lying. They're hallucinating. And with every new) Tj
T*
(model that comes out and promises to stay clean off drugs, it still hallucinates. An LLM can do) Tj
T*
(no wrong when all its failures are framed as neurological disorder. For my part, I hope there's) Tj
T*
(a real effort to teach these models to simply say "I don't know." But in the meantime, I'll) Tj
T*
(adopt the term for myself. If you ever suspect I'm lying, or catch me red-hande...) Tj
